[Papua and New Guinea] Keel (perforated) - Membranophone - Unlike the dorsal rib the perforated keel generally indicated the attachment of strung rattles underneath the drum - 1949 - Papua and New Guinea, Central and SE [South East] Coast - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Dorsal rib - Membranophone - The dorsal rib was noted to be a feature of many drums in this part of Papua - As a rule it was just a decoration although there were traces at times that suspensory cords might have been fixed to these ribs - 1949 - Papua and New Guinea, East Coast, [North-Eastern] Goodenough Bay - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Membranophone casing shapes (one) - A very old instrument noted in Kuanua country (New Britain) - It is bell-mouthed in design, has no handle and the grip point is set very close to the tympanum - Length approximately two feet - 1949 - New Guinea, New Britain, Kuanua - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Membranophone casing shapes (two) - This example noted in base of Collingwood Bay (Papua) - Length approximately three feet six inches - 1949 - Papua, North Eastern, Collingwood Bay - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Membranophone casing shapes (three) - This example noted in Orokaiva country (Papua) - Length approximately two feet six inches - 1949 - Papua, [Northern], Orokaiva - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Membranophone casing shapes (four) - This example noted as the more modern type of skin drum in the Koiari country near Oiribaiwa (Papua) - A similar type with a greater distance between the bowl shaped ends was seen in some villages of the coastal Nakanai people (New Britain) - 1949 - Papua, Oiribaiwa - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Membranophone casing shapes (five) - This example is typical of many skin drums which are unsymetrical in shape in the Wagi and Chimbu Valleys (Highlands of New Guinea) - Length approximately two feet nine inches - 1949 - New Guinea, Highlands, Wagi and Chimbu Valleys - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Membranophone casing shapes (six) - This example seen in Collingwood Bay - It is a very small instrument and seems to be replaced by the larger and more hourglass shaped casings - 1949 - Papua, North Eastern, Collingwood Bay - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Membranophone casing shapes (seven) - This tubular and near tubular shape was noted in parts of Eastern Papua and as far around as Logeo Island near Samarai - 1949 - Papua, Milne Bay [Eastern], Logea Island, Samarai - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Membranophone casing shapes (eight) - Length approximately fourteen inches - This flagon shaped casing was noted in the mid and upper Markham villages - 1949 - New Guinea, Morobe, Upper Markham - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Membranophone casing shapes (nine) - An unsymetrical skin drum easing from the Nakanai coast (New Britain) - This shape, slightly modified, is to be seen in some parts of the Wagi Valley (Highlands of New Guinea) - 1949 - New Guinea, New Britain and Highlands, Nakanai and Wagi Valley - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Membranophone casing shapes (ten) - This example of biconate casing with straight sides was noted well towards the base of Goodenough Bay on the southern coast - Length approximately two feet - 1949 - Papua, Milne Bay [Eastern], Goodenough Bay - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Membranophone casing shapes (eleven) - The elongated biconate shape was popular with Motu (Papua) drum makers early this century - Since then the hourglass shape has begun to predominate - Length approximately two feet six inches - 1949 - Papua, [Gulf?], Motu - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Membranophone casing shapes (twelve) - An example of the oldest membranophone casings preserved in the Wedan (Papua) villages - The handle was set high up on the casing towards the tympanum - Length approximately two feet six inches - 1949 - Papua, Eastern, Wedan - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Membranophone casing shapes (thirteen) - Casing shape from East Cape area (Papua) slightly modified from example number twelve - Here the handle is set lower down the casing - Length approximately two feet six inches - 1949 - Papua, East Cape area - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Membranophone casing shapes (fourteen) - Modern skin drum from Kuanua country (New Britain) - Here the handle is set well towards the tympanum - Length approximately two feet six inches - 1949 - New Guinea, New Britain, Kuanua - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Membranophone casing shapes (fifteen) - This example is typical of many drums to be seen at the present day around the coastal villages of the Kuanua people - 1949 - New Guinea, New Britain, Kuanua - R Sheridan

[Papua and New Guinea] Membranophone casing shapes (sixteen) - A very old skin drum casing from the Kuanua (New Britain) people - Some villagers hold the theory that this shape was expressly made so that the drum could be held comfortably over the legs of a seated player - Length approximately two feet six inches - 1949 - New Guinea, New Britain, Kuanua - R Sheridan
